# POLIS — Drawing in Isometric Perspective

The renderer is a fixed 2:1 isometric projection (`TW=64, TH=32`, ~line 1004):
`isoX=(x−y)·TW/2`, `isoY=(x+y)·TH/2`. Every `draw*` fn gets the tile's screen
anchor `sx,sy`; the **ground plane** of a point at grid offset `(ox,oy)` is:

```js
const P=(ox,oy)=>[sx+(ox-oy)*TW/2*z, sy+TH/2*z+(ox+oy)*TH/2*z];   // z = S.zoom
```

When adding or moving any geometry, check these — most building bugs are one of them:

- **Verticals stay vertical.** World height projects straight up the screen, so
  draw height by subtracting pixels (`-H`); poles, edges and walls are vertical
  screen lines. Never slant a vertical to "fake" 3-D.
- **Anchor to the ground, not to `sy`.** A prop's base must be the real ground
  point `P(ox,oy).y`, using the *same* offset math as the building. Don't reuse a
  roof/face y for something that sits on the ground.
- **Respect the footprint.** A building `vol(...,ax,ay,...)` covers `|ox|<ax`,
  `|oy|<ay`. Ground props (flags, signs, lamps, trees, vehicles) placed *inside*
  that box appear to erupt from the wall/roof. Plant them **outside** it — in
  front means larger `oy` (and draw them *after* the building so depth order is
  right; nearer = larger `ox+oy`).
- **Foreshorten the ground.** Horizontal spans squash in y: a circle on the
  ground is an ellipse with `ry ≈ rx·TH/TW = rx·0.5`. Use `ellipse`, not `arc`.
- **Seat verticals with a contact shadow.** A small dark ground ellipse at the
  foot of any pole/post sells "planted" over "floating".
- **Prefer the primitives.** `vol`/`box`/`cyl`/`facePt`/`quadF`/`archRoof`
  already place the 4 corners, faces and shading correctly — build from them
  instead of hand-rolling polygons that can drift off the iso axes.

## Three failure modes that recur on bigger builds

These bite multi-tile buildings (port, airport, venues, anything ≥2×2) and any
build that abuts a feature like water or a road. They pass `node --check` and a
single screenshot, then look broken once you **rotate the camera** or place a
**neighbour** beside them. Check all three whenever you add/edit such a build.

- **Orient to the WORLD, not the camera.** A draw fn that derives its frame from
  `rotD(...)` alone spins the building with the camera, so an edge that must face
  a fixed feature (a quay facing water, a frontage facing its road) ends up facing
  the wrong way in 2 of the 4 rotations — props then float over the river / hang
  off the deck and the "front" covers the land behind. Instead derive the frame
  from the world direction (e.g. `seaward = dominant grid dir to adjacent water`,
  then `[pvx,pvy]=rotD(seaward); avx=pvy; avy=-pvx`) so the build re-orients as the
  map turns. See `drawPort`/`portSeaward`. `drawCom` does the road-frontage version
  via `frontSide(x,y)` + a mirror.

- **A multi-tile building is painted at ONE tile — so it over-covers front
  neighbours.** A ≥2×2 build draws all its art when its *view-bottom* tile renders
  (`vqx+vqy` max, see the `lastX/lastY` pattern). A tall part that physically sits
  at the **back** of the footprint is then painted at front-tile time and covers a
  neighbour standing in front of it (the classic "warehouse drawn over the factory"
  bug). Fix by **splitting the draw across tiles by depth**: dispatch the tall
  landward/back structures from their *own* (earlier) tile and the front/ground
  detail from the front tile — pass a `phase` arg and call the draw fn twice from
  the two tiles (see the `port` case → `drawPort(...,'land')` / `'sea'`). Within a
  single pass, paint overlapping volumes **back-to-front** by a depth key
  (`depthOf=(du,dv)=>(avx+avy)*du+(pvx+pvy)*dv`, sort ascending), never in source
  order — source order looks fine in one rotation and wrong in the other three.

- **Ground the building, not just props.** The contact-shadow rule applies to
  whole buildings too. Lay the ground slab/apron **before** the structure in the
  same pass (and from the same/earlier tile), so the base reads as planted; if the
  slab is painted *after* (e.g. a later tile's diamond, or a deck poly drawn at the
  front tile while the building drew at the back tile) it clips the base and the
  building looks like it floats. Keep slab colours consistent (per-tile diamond ==
  unified deck) so the seam between passes is invisible.

### Example — forecourt flags (convention center, ~line 9178)

```js
// ❌ inside the footprint (oy=.22,.02 < building front face ~.32) → poles stab through the wall
for(let i=0;i<3;i++){ const [px,py]=P(.34, .42-i*.20); ... }

// ✅ on the forecourt in front of the facade, with a socket shadow
for(let i=0;i<3;i++){ const [px,py]=P(-.28+i*.28, .44);
  cx.fillStyle='rgba(12,18,26,.30)'; cx.beginPath(); cx.ellipse(px,py,1.7*z,0.85*z,0,0,7); cx.fill();
  cx.fillStyle='#cfd6dc'; cx.fillRect(px-.4*z, py-15*z, .8*z, 15*z); /* + pennant */ }
```
